<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-053-187 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 441 259</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Sept 25 1991 n1567 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Racal bid puts seal on split; Williams Holdings' bid for RacalElectronics has triggered the countdown to the group's break-up.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Clifford, Leon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The first step toward the ultimate breakup of Racal Electronicscame on Sep 17, 1991, when miniconglomerate Williams Holdings madea 703 million pounds sterling tender offer.andP;  Industry observershave long thought that the breakup of Racal was inevitable.andP;  Thecompany has been savagely cutting costs among its electronicsbusiness for nearly two years, particularly at computer networkspecialist Racal-Datacom, electronic design software firmRacal-Redac, and the Defence, Radar and Avionics Group.andP;  Twothousand jobs have also been cut.andP;  The cuts are helping; Racalmade 56 million pounds sterling in profit on total sales of 1billion pounds sterling, but the company made virtually nothinglast year, and the cuts probably will not save the company.andO;According to one analyst, no one wants the whole entity, and RacalChmn Ernest Harrison says that he may have to dismember thecompany himself to save it from a takeover.andP;  Harrison has deviseda three-phase plan to save it from a takeover and divorce thecompany from its Vodafone operation: spin-off or sell the RacalSecurity Group, and buy out the remaining core electronicsbusinesses to take it private.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Racal Electronics PLC (Management)Williams Holdings Inc. (Acquisitions, mergers, divestments).andO;Topic:     TakeoversReorganization.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Racal operating profit\loss 1991. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>